cal and scientific technologies around the turn of the twentieth century. These are popular topics of scholarly attention but have not, until now, been considered as interconnected topics within a single book. As such, this work connects several important, and usually separate academic subject areas and historical specialisms. The standards embedded in instrumentation created strict, but, ultimately arbitrary thresholds of what is categorised as normal and abnormal. Considering these standards from a long historical perspective reveals how these dividing lines shifted when pushed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aClassification.  aDisability.  aHealth.  aHistory.  aInterwar.  aMeasurement.  aMedical Humanities.  aNormalcy.  aStandardisation.  aTechnology.1 aMcGuire, Coreen Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526143167zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526143167zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526143167/original  a978-3-11-128248-0 Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA